			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Case Study in Grammar Engineering</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TiagoLAlves.html">Tiago L. Alves</a>, <a href="../profile/JoostVisser.html">Joost Visser</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_18">10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_18</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6a.html"><span class="tagM">T6A: Experience Reports</span></a><ul><li> As a ‘pearls’ case study, it reports experience and lessons learned from real grammar-engineering work.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Grammar engineering is treated as an evolving artifact, and the case study focuses on how it is maintained/changed.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5c.html"><span class="tagL">T5C: Testing</span></a><ul><li> It typically stresses validation/testing practices for grammars as engineered artifacts.
</li></ul></li></ul>
